Practice Problems — Topic 4
Q1. Thermal resistance calculation chain:
A MOSFET dissipates 3W. Package: D2PAK. Datasheet: θ_JC = 5°C/W. Thermal pad: θ_CS = 0.8°C/W. PCB copper pour 150mm²: θ_SA = 30/1.5 = 20°C/W. Ambient = 40°C.
(a) θ_JA total
(b) T_junction
(c) Is T_J within limits (T_J_max = 150°C)? What is the margin?
(d) If ambient rises to 70°C (hot enclosure): recalculate T_J. Still within limits?
(e) To maintain T_J < 125°C (with 25°C safety margin) at 70°C ambient: what maximum θ_JA is allowed? What change to the layout achieves this? (Increase copper area or add heatsink)
Q2. Thermal via array sizing:
A DPAK MOSFET has 4mm × 6mm = 24mm² exposed pad. Dissipates 4W. Via parameters: diameter 0.4mm, plating thickness 25µm, PCB thickness 1.6mm, k_Cu = 400 W/(m·K).
(a) Thermal resistance per single via: R_via = t_PCB/(k_Cu × A_copper) where A_copper = π × d × t_plating
(b) Maximum vias fitting in 24mm² at 1.0mm pitch (square array)
(c) R_via_array with maximum vias
(d) If heat must travel from pad to opposite layer (bottom copper), and then spread over 100mm² bottom copper (θ_spreading = 30/1.0 = 30°C/W): total θ from junction to ambient = θ_JC + R_via_array + θ_spreading + θ_TIM. Find total and resulting T_J at T_ambient=40°C.
(e) Is a separate heatsink needed? What is the remaining margin to 150°C T_J_max?
Q3. Heatsink selection:
A forward converter has four secondary diodes, each dissipating 2W (total 8W). Diodes are in TO-220 packages. θ_JC = 3°C/W each. θ_CS (with pad) = 1.5°C/W. T_ambient = 50°C, T_J_max = 150°C.
(a) Required θ_JA per diode
(b) Required θ_SA per diode
(c) If all four diodes share one common heatsink and each adds thermal resistance in parallel (total heat = 8W, θ_SA_heatsink needed for total power): required heatsink θ_SA
(d) Required heatsink surface area for natural convection
(e) A standard heatsink (25mm × 50mm × 15mm tall, with fins) has approximately 80cm² surface area. Calculate its θ_SA. Is it adequate?
Q4. Transformer thermal management:
Your flyback capstone transformer (EE30 core) has P_Cu = 0.290W and P_core = 0.046W. Ambient inside enclosure = 50°C.
(a) Total transformer loss
(b) The transformer sits on the PCB bobbin pins. The thermal path from core to PCB is approximately θ_transformer_to_PCB = 30°C/W (poor thermal contact through bobbin pins). Find transformer temperature rise above PCB.
(c) If PCB is at 60°C (above ambient due to other component heating): transformer temperature
(d) At what total transformer loss would the transformer exceed 100°C (typical ferrite safe operating temperature)? Is your design within this limit?
(e) If you wanted to reduce transformer temperature, name three design changes (one related to core material, one related to wire choice, one related to mechanical arrangement on the PCB).
Q5. Complete thermal design review for your capstone:
Compile a thermal analysis table for all major components in your 30W flyback converter.
Assume: T_ambient = 50°C, PCB copper provides θ_SA where applicable.
For each component, calculate T_J or T_surface:
(a) MOSFET (STD5NK60Z, DPAK): P=2.482W, θ_JC=10°C/W, 12 vias + 250mm² copper pour (θ_SA ≈ 12°C/W), θ_TIM=0.5°C/W
(b) Secondary diode (MBRS4200T3G, SMB package): P=1.0W, θ_JC=15°C/W, PCB copper 80mm² (θ_SA ≈ 37.5°C/W)
(c) RCD clamp resistor (2.2kΩ, through-hole 2W rated): P=1.116W. A through-hole resistor relies entirely on its own body for heat dissipation. θ_JA ≈ 80°C/W for a 2W axial resistor. Find T_body.
(d) Transformer: P_total = 0.336W, θ_transformer_to_PCB = 30°C/W. T_transformer surface.
(e) Which component has the highest temperature? Is any component outside its safe operating range? What action would you take?
